ioch, and their influence had spread throughout western Europe and the Mediterranean. Duke William's victory at Hastings and the resulting Anglo-Norman union brought England into the mainstream of European history and culture, with far-reaching consequences for Western civilisation. These specially commissioned studies are concerned with the achievements of the cross-Channel realm. They make a major contribution to an understanding of the hundred years that witnessed great change and major developments in English and Norman government and society. There are surveys of the two constituent parts, of Normandy under the Angevin kings, of the place of kingdom and duchy in the politics and cultureof the North Sea, and of the parallel Norman achievement in the Mediterranean. There are overviews both of secular administration and of the church, and a study of 'feudalism' and lordship. Within the broad field of cultural history, there are discussions of language, literature, the writing of history, and ecclesiastical architecture. Contributors LESLEY ABRAMS, MATTHEW BENNETT, MARJORIE CHIBNALL, CHRISTOPHER HARPER-BILL, ELISABETH VAN HOUTS,EMMA MASON, RICHARD PLANT, CASSANDRA POTTS, DANIEL POWER, IAN SHORT, ANN WILLIAMS.  aMode of access: Internet via World Wide Web.  aIn English.0 aDescription based on online resource; title from PDF title page (publisher's Web site, viewed 06. Mrz 2024) 0aNormansvHandbooks, manuals, etczGreat Britain. 0aNormanszGreat BritainvHandbooks, manuals, etc. 4aMedieval History. 7aHISTORY / Europe / Great Britain / General.2bisacsh  aAnglo-Norman.  aConquest.  aCulture.  aEurope.  aMedieval History.  aNormandy.1 aAbrams, Lesley, econtributor.4ctb4https://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/ctb1 aBennett, Matthew, econtributor.4ctb4https://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/ctb1 aChibnall, Marjorie, econtributor.4ctb4https://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/ctb1 aHarper-Bill, Christopher, econtributor.4ctb4https: